<concept id="pickstyle-except-os-x" xml:lang="en-US">
   <title id="title__Toc50995418">PICKSTYLE (EXCEPT OS X) System Variable</title>
   <conbody>
      <section><title>Pick style</title><p>Specifies the selection of groups and associative hatches. The value of PICKSTYLE is stored as a bitcode using the sum of the values of all selected options.</p><p>Ctrl-H toggles PICKSTYLE 0/1 if 0 or 1 and 2/3 if 2 or 3.</p><p><table id="table_r32_ncz_hnb">
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1*" />
                  <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2" colwidth="3*" />
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/type" />
                        <entry><p conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/short" /></entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/saved_in" />
                        <entry>
                           <p conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/registry" />
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/range" />
                        <entry><p>0 to 3</p>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/default_value" />
                        <entry><p>1</p>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry conkeyref="system_variable_warehouse/possible_values" />
                        <entry><p>0: No group selection or associative hatch selection</p>
                           <p>1: Group selection if a member of a selectable group is selected, all members of the group are selected</p>
                           <p>2: Associative hatch selection the hatch and its boundary are selected, no matter what is picked (the hatch or the boundary).</p>
                           <p>3: Group selection and associative hatch selection</p>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </table></p></section>
   </conbody>
</concept>
